title.narrative: Disaster Mitigation and Preparation. Health Support. Education Support. Basic Infrastructure

description.narrative: This award strives to save lives, alleviate suffering, and minimize the economic costs of conflict, disasters and displacement. Humanitarian assistance is provided on the basis of need according to principles of universality, impartiality and human dignity. More specifically, this includes Crisis Response Training for Responders. Equipping the Training Center of the Mexican Civil Association Security and Rescue Unit. Institutional development for Mexico's National Civil Protection School (Phase I). Improvement of DIF's National Center for Model Care, Research, Training for the Rehabilitation of Blind and the Visually Impaired (OOC 17-18). DIF Granja Hogar Shelter in Ciudad Juárez - $15,000. Training workshop on pattern recognition of volcano-seismic signals in volcano observatories in Central America. Secretaría de Marina (SEMAR) Canine Equipment. Casa Cuna Coyoacan Orphanage. Pediatric Audiology Equipment for ARSOBO in Sonora Mexico 2019. Casa Cuna Coyoacan Orphanage- Phase II. Improvement of DIF's Prosthetics and Ortothics workshop 'Gaby Brimmer' National Center (FY19/20). Strengthening Mexico's healthcare and public health sector capacity to prepare for and respond to Public Health Emergencies. Support to Civil Protection's Popocapetl volcano response in Mexico. Institutional development for Mexico's National Civil Protection School. Shelter. ENAPROC Temporary Space Renovation. Improving the Emergency Response Capabilities of Municipal Firefighters in Ciudad Juarez. Mexico SEDENA-Urban Search and Rescue Train & Equip. Mexico City 2018 Vehicular Rescue Challenge. DIF Children's Shelter Renovation- Tijuana, Baja California. Bio Surveillance Symposium, Panama City, Panama. Enhance the Capabilities of the National Civil Protection School (ENAPROC). Institutional development for Mexico's National Civil Protection School Phase II (FY19). Medical Equipment for 'La Gaviota' Center. Flood Early Warning System - Mexico '19-'20. Water Tank and Water Pump systems for Cobach Eusebio Francisco Kino School in Magdalena, Sonora. Improvement of National Center for Model Care, Research, Training for the Rehabilitation of Blind and the Visually Impaired. Upgrade for Operational Center for Contingency Assistance (COPAC) Mobile Medical Units. Casa Amiga Homeless Shelter Renovation. Raramuri Indigenous Kitchen. Mexico Secretariat of National Defense (SEDENA)-Urban Search and Rescue Train & Equip. Equipment for 'La Mansión' Children's Shelter. Mexico SEMAR-Urban Search and Rescue Train & Equip.

To save lives, alleviate suffering, and minimize the economic costs of conflict, disasters and displacement. Humanitarian assistance is provided on the basis of need according to principles of universality, impartiality and human dignity. It is often organized by sectors, but requires an integrated, coordinated and/or multi-sectoral approach to be most effective. Emergency operations will foster the transition from relief, through recovery, to development, but they cannot and will not replace the development investments necessary to reduce chronic poverty or establish just social services.

description.narrative: In FY 2017, the United States will partner with Mexico to consolidate and institutionalize progress made as a result of ongoing bilateral cooperation, particularly through the Merida Initiative. By weakening transnational criminal organizations (TCOs), reforming the institutions that sustain the rule of law, protecting human rights, creating a 21st century border, and building stronger and more resilient communities, the United States and Mexico will ensure greater prosperity and inclusive economic growth on both sides of the border. To support the President's Global Climate Change (GCC) Initiative, a strong partnership with the Government of Mexico and other stakeholders will promote clean energy adoption, energy efficiency, low carbon development, and sustainable land use and forest management to reduce greenhouse gas emissions. Mexico is a global non-proliferation partner and related assistance will focus on enhancing Mexico's capabilities and commitment. Mexico continues to be a strong partner of the initiatives that complement the United States' programs to address the root causes of unlawful migration from Central America.
